13 EXPLANATION
14 The inclusion of this explanation does not constitute agreement with
15 the explanation’s substance by the members of the general assembly.
16 Under current law, the driver of a motor vehicle and
17 passengers, other than passengers being transported in a
18 motor vehicle designed, maintained, or used primarily for the
19 transportation of persons for compensation, and passengers
20 being transported in the living quarters of a motor home,
21 motorsports recreational vehicle, manufactured or mobile home,
22 travel trailer, or fifth-wheel travel trailer, are prohibited
23 from possessing in the passenger area of the motor vehicle
24 an open or unsealed bottle, can, jar, or other receptacle
25 containing an alcoholic beverage while the vehicle is operated
26 on a public street or highway. An open or unsealed receptacle
27 containing an alcoholic beverage may be transported in the
28 trunk of the motor vehicle or behind the last upright seat of
29 the motor vehicle if the motor vehicle does not have a trunk.
30 This bill similarly prohibits a driver and passenger from
31 possessing an open container of an otherwise lawful beverage
32 containing tetrahydrocannabinol (THC). A lawful beverage
33 containing THC must not exceed 0.3 percent on a dry weight
34 basis, is limited to 4 milligrams of THC (on a dry weight
35 basis) per serving and 10 milligrams of THC (on a dry weight
